Q3. Neural Networks: Structure, Activation, Representation
(a) Non-linear activations

Non-linear activation functions allow neural networks to learn complex,
 non-linear relationships in data. Without them, 
 the network would behave like a linear model regardless of depth.
  This would severely limit its expressive power.

(b) Deep vs shallow models

Deep networks learn hierarchical features, where lower layers capture simple patterns 
and higher layers combine them into complex representations.
 Shallow models like logistic regression cannot build such multi-level abstractions.
  Hence, deep models are more powerful for complex tasks like vision and language.

1) RNN Families & Use-Cases
(a) Mapping tasks
Next-word prediction → many-to-many (aligned)
Each input word produces an output at the same time step (predict next token sequentially).
Sentiment of a sentence → many-to-one
Entire sequence is processed to produce a single output label.
NER → many-to-many (aligned)
Each input word gets a corresponding output tag.
Machine translation → many-to-many (unaligned)
Input and output sequences differ in length and alignment.
(b) Unrolling & BPTT

Unrolling expands the RNN across time steps,
 turning it into a deep network where each step shares the same weights.
This allows gradients to be computed across time using Backpropagation Through Time (BPTT).

(c) Weight sharing
Advantage: Reduces number of parameters and improves generalization.
Limitation: Limits flexibility since the same transformation is applied at every time step.
2) Vanishing Gradients & Remedies
(a) Vanishing gradient problem

Gradients shrink exponentially as they are backpropagated through many time steps.
This makes it difficult for the model to learn long-range dependencies.
As a result, earlier information is often forgotten.

(b) Architectural solutions
LSTM: Uses gates and cell state to preserve gradients over long sequences.
GRU: Simplifies gating while still maintaining better gradient flow.
(c) Training technique

Gradient clipping prevents gradients
from becoming too small or too large by restricting their values.
This stabilizes training and helps maintain effective learning.

3) LSTM Gates & Cell State
(a) Gates
Forget gate (sigmoid): Decides what information to discard from the cell state.
Input gate (sigmoid + tanh): Controls what new information to add.
Output gate (sigmoid): Determines what part of the cell state to output.
(b) Linear path

The cell state allows information to flow with minimal modification through time. 
This creates a near-linear path for gradients, reducing vanishing effects.

(c) Remember vs expose

“What to remember” is controlled by the forget and input gates deciding what stays in memory.
“What to expose” is controlled by the output gate determining what is sent to the next layer.

4) Self-Attention
(a) Q, K, V

Query represents the current token asking for information,
Key represents all tokens’ identities, and Value contains the actual information.
Attention scores are computed using Q and K, then applied to V.

(b) Dot-product attention
Attention
(𝑄,𝐾,𝑉)=softmax(𝑄𝐾𝑇𝑑𝑘)𝑉Attention(Q,K,V)=softmax(dkQKT)V
(c) Why divide by 𝑑𝑘dk?

It prevents dot products from becoming too large as dimensionality increases.
This keeps the softmax stable and gradients well-behaved.

5) Multi-Head Attention & Residuals
(a) Multi-head attention

Multiple heads allow the model to focus on different parts of the sequence simultaneously.
Each head learns different relationships, improving representation power.

(b) Add & Norm

Residual connections help gradients flow easily through deep networks.
Layer normalization stabilizes training and speeds up convergence.

(c) Example relation

One head might capture subject-verb agreement,
while another captures coreference between pronouns and nouns.

6) Encoder–Decoder with Masked Attention
(a) Masked self-attention

It prevents the decoder from seeing future tokens during training.
This ensures predictions depend only on past outputs, maintaining causality.

(b) Self vs cross-attention

Encoder self-attention relates words within the input sequence.
Cross-attention connects decoder tokens with encoder outputs
to incorporate source information.

(c) Inference generation

During inference, the model generates one token
at a time using previously generated outputs as input.
Each new token is appended and fed back into the decoder.
This process continues until an end token is produced.